                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100240">Flanders</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1525" notBefore="1501">16th century, first quarter</origDate>. The feasts in the calendar point to the diocese of <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100294">Cambrai</placeName>. The use of feminine suffixes in the prayers indicates that the manuscript was commissioned by or for a woman. (For examples of suffixes, see <locus from="208v" to="208v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <quote>indigne famule tue</quote>, <locus from="211v" to="211v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <quote>peccatrici</quote>).</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>
                                <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102649">François d'Anglure</persName>, baron of <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100297">Boursault</placeName>, owned the manuscript in the early 16th century. The notes on <locus from="2r" to="3v" scheme="folios"/> place the manuscript in his ownership in <date when="1523"/> at the latest. Its later fate is unknown, but by the late 18th century the manuscript belonged to the library of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102647">Charles XIII</persName> at <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100295">Rosersberg Palace</placeName>, where it had the signum <quote>n. 1014</quote>. According to the note on <locus from="SL2v" to="SL2v" scheme="folios"/> it was later acquired by a Frenchman, then belonged to <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102648">Gustaf Göran Gabriel Oxenstierna</persName> and from him the manuscript went to <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102646">Reinhold Rudbeck</persName> (senior) at <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100296">Edsberg Palace</placeName>. The additions on <locus from="4r" to="4r" scheme="folios"/> may be initials of a later owner.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Acquired from <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102646">Reinhold Rudbeck</persName> in <date when="1879-01-29"/>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
